---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import WeekNumberCalculator from '../components/WeekNumberCalculator.jsx';
---

<Layout
	title="Week Number Calculator — ISO Week Number | Clockr"
	description="Find the ISO week number for any date. See the week's date range and how many weeks remain in the year. Free week number calculator."
>
	<div class="wnc-page">
		<div class="wnc-header">
			<div class="wnc-eyebrow">
				<span class="wnc-eyebrow-square" aria-hidden="true"></span>
				Calendar & Dates
			</div>
			<h1 class="wnc-title">
				<span class="wnc-gradient">Week Number</span><br />
				<span class="wnc-gradient">Calculator</span>
			</h1>
			<p class="wnc-subtitle">
				Find the ISO week number for any date
			</p>
		</div>

		<WeekNumberCalculator client:load />

		<!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
		<section class="wnc-how">
			<h2 class="wnc-section-title">How it works</h2>
			<div class="wnc-how-card">
				<p>
					ISO week numbers are a standard way to label weeks in the year,
					defined by ISO 8601. Instead of counting from 1 January, each week is
					numbered consistently so that week boundaries always fall on Monday
					through Sunday. Businesses, logistics companies, and project managers
					rely on ISO weeks for reporting, production schedules, and
					cross-border coordination because everyone agrees on which week a date
					belongs to.
				</p>
				<p>
					Week 1 of a year is the week that contains the first Thursday of
					that year — equivalently, the week that contains 4 January. This
					means the first few days of January may belong to week 52 or 53 of the
					previous year, and the last few days of December may already belong to
					week 1 of the next. Clockr uses this ISO rule so your result matches
					what you would see in Excel, SAP, and most European business systems.
				</p>
				<p>
					Most years have exactly 52 ISO weeks, but roughly one in five or six
					years has 53. This happens when 1 January falls on a Thursday, or on a
					Wednesday in a leap year — or when 31 December falls on a Thursday
					(or Wednesday in a leap year). This calculator determines the correct
					week count for the ISO year your date belongs to, so weeks remaining
					in the year are always accurate.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- FAQ -->
		<section class="wnc-faq">
			<h2 class="wnc-section-title">Frequently asked questions</h2>
			<div class="wnc-faq-list">
				<details class="wnc-faq-item">
					<summary class="wnc-faq-question"
						>What is an ISO week number?</summary
					>
					<div class="wnc-faq-answer">
						<p>
							An ISO week number is a label from 1 to 52 (or occasionally 53)
							assigned to each Monday–Sunday week under the ISO 8601 standard.
							It provides a consistent, internationally recognised way to refer
							to a specific week regardless of which month it spans. Many
							European countries and global industries use ISO weeks as their
							default week numbering system.
						</p>
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="wnc-faq-item">
					<summary class="wnc-faq-question"
						>What week of the year is it today?</summary
					>
					<div class="wnc-faq-answer">
						<p>
							Click the "This week" button in the quick-reference section above,
							or simply load this page — the date field defaults to today and
							shows the current ISO week number instantly. The result includes
							the full Monday–Sunday range for this week and how many weeks are
							left in the ISO year.
						</p>
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="wnc-faq-item">
					<summary class="wnc-faq-question"
						>How many weeks are there in a year?</summary
					>
					<div class="wnc-faq-answer">
						<p>
							In the ISO system, most years contain 52 weeks. However, some
							years — roughly one in five or six — contain 53 weeks because of
							how week 1 is defined relative to the calendar. A standard
							calendar year has 52 weeks plus one or two extra days, and those
							extra days occasionally create an additional full ISO week.
						</p>
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="wnc-faq-item">
					<summary class="wnc-faq-question"
						>Why do some years have 53 weeks?</summary
					>
					<div class="wnc-faq-answer">
						<p>
							A year gains a 53rd ISO week when 1 January falls on a Thursday, or
							on a Wednesday in a leap year. The same applies when 31 December
							falls on a Thursday (or Wednesday in a leap year). In those cases
							an extra full Monday–Sunday week fits into the ISO year without
							being absorbed into week 1 of the following year.
						</p>
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="wnc-faq-item">
					<summary class="wnc-faq-question"
						>Does the week start on Sunday or Monday?</summary
					>
					<div class="wnc-faq-answer">
						<p>
							Under ISO 8601, the week starts on Monday and ends on Sunday. This
							is the opposite of the convention used in the United States, where
							weeks are often considered to run Sunday through Saturday. This
							calculator follows the ISO Monday-start rule, which is the
							standard for business and manufacturing worldwide.
						</p>
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="wnc-faq-item">
					<summary class="wnc-faq-question"
						>How is week 1 of the year determined?</summary
					>
					<div class="wnc-faq-answer">
						<p>
							ISO week 1 is the week that contains the first Thursday of the
							calendar year. A simpler equivalent rule: week 1 is the week
							containing 4 January. This means 1–3 January might belong to the
							last week of the previous ISO year, while 29–31 December might
							already be in week 1 of the next ISO year.
						</p>
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="wnc-faq-item">
					<summary class="wnc-faq-question"
						>Why are week numbers used in business and manufacturing?</summary
					>
					<div class="wnc-faq-answer">
						<p>
							Week numbers simplify planning when work spans month boundaries.
							Production schedules, sales reports, payroll periods, and project
							milestones are often organised by week rather than by calendar
							month. ISO week numbers are unambiguous across countries and
							software systems, making them the preferred choice for supply
							chains, ERP systems, and international teams.
						</p>
					</div>
				</details>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- RELATED TOOLS -->
		<div class="wnc-related">
			<h3 class="wnc-related-title">Related tools</h3>
			<div class="wnc-related-grid">
				<a href="/day-of-week" class="wnc-related-card"
					><span class="wnc-related-name"
						>Day of the Week Calculator</span
					></a
				>
				<a href="/date-calculator" class="wnc-related-card"
					><span class="wnc-related-name">Date Calculator</span></a
				>
				<a href="/leap-year" class="wnc-related-card"
					><span class="wnc-related-name">Leap Year Checker</span></a
				>
				<a href="/business-days" class="wnc-related-card"
					><span class="wnc-related-name">Business Days Calculator</span></a
				>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</Layout>

<style is:global>
	.wnc-page {
		max-width: 800px;
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: 60px 24px;
	}

	.wnc-header {
		text-align: center;
		margin-bottom: 48px;
	}

	.wnc-eyebrow {
		display: inline-flex;
		align-items: center;
		gap: 8px;
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 12px;
		font-weight: 700;
		letter-spacing: 3px;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, #10b981, #84cc16);
		-webkit-background-clip: text;
		-webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
		background-clip: text;
		margin-bottom: 16px;
	}

	.wnc-eyebrow-square {
		width: 8px;
		height: 8px;
		border-radius: 2px;
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, #10b981, #84cc16);
		flex-shrink: 0;
		-webkit-text-fill-color: initial;
	}

	.wnc-title {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 64px;
		font-weight: 900;
		letter-spacing: -3px;
		line-height: 1.05;
		margin-bottom: 16px;
	}

	.wnc-gradient {
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, #10b981, #84cc16);
		-webkit-background-clip: text;
		-webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
		background-clip: text;
	}

	.wnc-subtitle {
		font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
		font-size: 16px;
		color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);
		line-height: 1.6;
	}

	.wnc-input-wrap {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		align-items: center;
		gap: 12px;
		margin-bottom: 48px;
	}

	.wnc-label {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 14px;
		font-weight: 600;
		color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.6);
		letter-spacing: 0.5px;
	}

	.wnc-input {
		background: #0c0c0c;
		border: 1px solid rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.3);
		border-radius: 12px;
		padding: 16px 24px;
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 24px;
		font-weight: 700;
		color: #ffffff;
		text-align: center;
		outline: none;
		cursor: pointer;
		transition: border-color 0.2s ease;
		min-width: 280px;
	}

	.wnc-input:focus {
		border-color: rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.8);
		box-shadow: 0 0 20px rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.15);
	}

	.wnc-results {
		margin-bottom: 48px;
	}

	.wnc-main-card {
		background: #0c0c0c;
		border: 1px solid rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.2);
		border-radius: 20px;
		padding: 40px;
		text-align: center;
		box-shadow: 0 0 40px rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.06);
	}

	.wnc-week-title {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 56px;
		font-weight: 900;
		letter-spacing: -3px;
		line-height: 1.1;
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, #10b981, #84cc16);
		-webkit-background-clip: text;
		-webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
		background-clip: text;
		margin-bottom: 16px;
	}

	.wnc-week-range {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 20px;
		font-weight: 600;
		color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.7);
		margin-bottom: 16px;
		line-height: 1.5;
	}

	.wnc-remaining {
		font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
		font-size: 16px;
		color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.45);
		line-height: 1.5;
	}

	.wnc-quick {
		margin-bottom: 48px;
	}

	.wnc-quick-grid {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
		gap: 12px;
	}

	.wnc-quick-btn {
		background: #0c0c0c;
		border: 1px solid rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.15);
		border-radius: 12px;
		padding: 16px 12px;
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 14px;
		font-weight: 600;
		color: #fff;
		cursor: pointer;
		transition:
			border-color 0.2s ease,
			background 0.2s ease;
	}

	.wnc-quick-btn:hover {
		border-color: rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.5);
		background: rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.04);
	}

	.wnc-section-title {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 20px;
		font-weight: 700;
		color: #fff;
		margin-bottom: 16px;
	}

	.wnc-how {
		margin-bottom: 48px;
	}

	.wnc-how-card {
		background: #0c0c0c;
		border: 1px solid rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.15);
		border-radius: 14px;
		padding: 24px;
	}

	.wnc-how-card p {
		font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
		font-size: 15px;
		color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.55);
		line-height: 1.7;
		margin: 0 0 16px;
	}

	.wnc-how-card p:last-child {
		margin-bottom: 0;
	}

	.wnc-faq {
		margin-bottom: 48px;
	}

	.wnc-faq-list {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 8px;
	}

	.wnc-faq-item {
		background: #0c0c0c;
		border: 1px solid rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.15);
		border-radius: 14px;
		overflow: hidden;
	}

	.wnc-faq-question {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 15px;
		font-weight: 600;
		padding: 18px 24px;
		cursor: pointer;
		list-style: none;
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, #10b981, #84cc16);
		-webkit-background-clip: text;
		-webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
		background-clip: text;
	}

	.wnc-faq-question::-webkit-details-marker {
		display: none;
	}

	.wnc-faq-question::after {
		content: '+';
		float: right;
		font-size: 18px;
		font-weight: 700;
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, #10b981, #84cc16);
		-webkit-background-clip: text;
		-webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
		background-clip: text;
	}

	.wnc-faq-item[open] .wnc-faq-question::after {
		content: '−';
	}

	.wnc-faq-answer {
		padding: 0 24px 18px;
	}

	.wnc-faq-answer p {
		font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
		font-size: 14px;
		color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.55);
		line-height: 1.7;
		margin: 0;
	}

	.wnc-related {
		border-top: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
		padding-top: 40px;
	}

	.wnc-related-title {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 20px;
		font-weight: 700;
		color: #fff;
		margin-bottom: 16px;
	}

	.wnc-related-grid {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
		gap: 12px;
	}

	.wnc-related-card {
		background: #0c0c0c;
		border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
		border-radius: 12px;
		padding: 20px 16px;
		text-align: center;
		text-decoration: none;
		transition: border-color 0.2s ease;
	}

	.wnc-related-card:hover {
		border-color: rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.4);
	}

	.wnc-related-name {
		font-family: 'Outfit', sans-serif;
		font-size: 14px;
		font-weight: 600;
		background: linear-gradient(135deg, #10b981, #84cc16);
		-webkit-background-clip: text;
		-webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
		background-clip: text;
	}

	@media (max-width: 600px) {
		.wnc-title {
			font-size: 44px;
			letter-spacing: -2px;
		}

		.wnc-week-title {
			font-size: 40px;
			letter-spacing: -2px;
		}

		.wnc-quick-grid {
			grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
		}

		.wnc-related-grid {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}
	}
</style>
